<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,681,844,870]" box="[264,681,844,870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<heading bold="true" box="[264,681,844,870]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,681,844,870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[400,553,844,870]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Bactrodinae">Bactrodinae</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Stal" box="[560,681,844,870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" refString="Stal, C. (1866) Bidrag till Reduvidernas kannedom. Ofversigt af Konglinga Vetenskaps Akademiens Forhandlingar, 23 (9), 235 - 302." type="journal article" year="1866">
Stål, 
<number box="[622,681,844,870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1866.0">1866</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,919,1505]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Small and slender insects (
<figureCitation box="[584,655,919,945]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[264,368,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[344,1236,549,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[335,1252,529,1834]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bactrodes femoratus. General aspect. Scale line: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156880/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Fig. 
<number box="[641,655,919,945]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Head transverse. Interocular sulcus weakly developed or obsolete. Antenna filiform, inserted laterally before eyes. First antennal segment longest. Trichobothria of antennal segment II placed 
<number box="[859,902,999,1025]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
basally and 
<number box="[1060,1075,999,1025]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1.0">1</number>
distally in the adult (
<bibRefCitation author="Wygodzinsky" box="[272,635,1039,1065]" pageId="2" pageNumber="15" refString="Wygodzinsky, P. &amp; S. Lodhi. (1989) Atlas of antennal trichobothria in the Pachynomidae and Reduviidae (Heteroptera). Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 97, 371 - 393." type="journal article" year="1989">
Wygodzinsky &amp; Lodhi, 
<number box="[572,635,1039,1065]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Rostrum long, slender, moderately curved; segment II always longest. Eyes protruded, rounded in lateral view. Ocelli invariably present, inserted on wide separated protuberances. Prothorax projecting beneath head. Posterior lobe of pronotum longer than anterior. Scutellum and postscutellum triangular. Tibial spur conspicuous. Tarsi three­segmented, segment II longest. Hemelytra distinctly divided into chorion and membrane, membrane with one cell. Venation specialized. 
<collectingCountry box="[1132,1191,1239,1265]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Hind</collectingCountry>
wing with submarginal subcosta, no secondary veins, and with a narrow postcubital sector with Pcu and 
<number box="[314,324,1319,1345]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1.0">1</number>
A veins, these almost straight and parallel (
<bibRefCitation author="Davis" box="[840,988,1319,1345]" pageId="2" pageNumber="14" refString="Davis, N. T. (1969) Contribution to the morphology and phylogeny of the Reduvioidea (Hemiptera: Heteroptera). Part IV. The harpactoroid complex. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 62, 74 - 94." type="journal article" year="1969">
Davis, 
<number box="[925,988,1319,1345]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1969.0">1969</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Nymphs with 
<number box="[1176,1190,1319,1345]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="3.0">3</number>
abdominal scent glands on anterior margin of terga 
<number box="[764,809,1359,1385]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6</number>
. Median process of pygophore bifurcated. Vermiform gland and subrectal gland absent, pseudospermathecae well developed (
<bibRefCitation author="Davis" pageId="2" pageNumber="14" refString="Davis, N. T. (1969) Contribution to the morphology and phylogeny of the Reduvioidea (Hemiptera: Heteroptera). Part IV. The harpactoroid complex. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 62, 74 - 94." type="journal article" year="1969">
Davis, 
<number box="[264,324,1439,1465]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1969.0">1969</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</paragraph>
